Problem 1

The us_gasoline series consists of weekly data for supplies of US finished motor gasoline product, from 2 February 1991 to 20 January 2017. The units are in “million barrels per day”. Consider only the data to the end of 2004.

gas <- us_gasoline |> filter(year(Week) <= 2004)

  1. Fit a harmonic regression with trend to the data. Experiment with changing the number Fourier terms. Select the appropriate number of Fourier terms to include by minimising the AICc or CV value. Plot the observed gasoline and fitted values and comment on what you see.

  2. Plot the residuals of the final model using the gg_tsresiduals() function and comment on these.

  3. Generate forecasts for the next year of data and plot these along with the actual data for 2005. Comment on the forecasts.

  4. Fit a dynamic harmonic regression model to these data. How does it compare to the regression model you fitted in part (a)?

  5. Check the residuals from both models and comment on what you see.

Problem 1 Solutions

  1. Fit a harmonic regression with trend to the data. Experiment with changing the number Fourier terms. Select the appropriate number of Fourier terms to include by minimising the AICc or CV value. Plot the observed gasoline and fitted values and comment on what you see.
gas <- us_gasoline |> filter(year(Week) <= 2004)
gas |> autoplot(Barrels)

fit <- gas |>
  model(
    fourier1 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 1)),
    fourier2 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 2)),
    fourier3 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 3)),
    fourier4 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 4)),
    fourier5 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 5)),
    fourier6 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 6)),
    fourier7 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 7)),
    fourier8 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 8)),
    fourier9 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 9)),
    fourier10 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 10)),
    fourier11 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 11)),
    fourier12 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 12)),
    fourier13 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 13)),
    fourier14 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 14)),
    fourier15 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 15))
  )

glance(fit) |>
  arrange(AICc) |>
  select(.model, AICc, CV)
# Best model has order 7
gas |>
  autoplot(Barrels, col = "gray") +
  geom_line(
    data = augment(fit) |> filter(.model == "fourier7"),
    aes(y = .fitted), col = "blue"
  )

This seems to have captured the annual seasonality quite well.

  1. Plot the residuals of the final model using the gg_tsresiduals() function and comment on these.
fit |>
  select(fourier7) |>
  gg_tsresiduals()

The correlations are very small.

  1. Generate forecasts for the next year of data and plot these along with the actual data for 2005. Comment on the forecasts.
fit |>
  select("fourier7") |>
  forecast(h = "1 year") |>
  autoplot(filter_index(us_gasoline, "2000" ~ "2006"))

The forecasts fit pretty well for the first six months, but not so well after that.

  1. Fit a dynamic harmonic regression model to these data. How does it compare to the regression model you fitted in part (a)?
fit <- gas |>
  model(
    fourier7 = TSLM(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K = 7)),
    dhm = ARIMA(Barrels ~ trend() + fourier(K=7) + PDQ(0,0,0))
  )
fit
gas |>
  autoplot(Barrels, col = "gray") +
  geom_line(
    data = augment(fit) |> filter(.model == "fourier7"),
    aes(y = .fitted), col = "blue"
  ) +
  geom_line(
    data = augment(fit) |> filter(.model == "dhm"),
    aes(y = .fitted), col = "red"
  )

fit |>
  forecast(h="2 years") |>
  autoplot(gas, level=NULL)

These two models are almost identical. The additional MA(1) parameter in the DHM only affects the first point forecast, and leads to slightly narrower the prediction intervals.

  1. Check the residuals from both models and comment on what you see.
fit |>
  select(fourier7) |>
  gg_tsresiduals()

fit |>
  select(dhm) |>
  gg_tsresiduals()

The tiny spike at lag 1 in the ACF of the regression model is corrected in the DHM model.

Problem 2

Experiment with using NNETAR() on the following retail data. Compare its performance to that of ETS and ARIMA models. Use the data from 2018 for testing.

retail <- aus_retail |>
  filter(`Series ID` == "A3349849A", year(Month) < 2018)

Problem 2

retail |> autoplot(Turnover)

fit <- retail |>
  model(
    ets = ETS(Turnover),
    arima = ARIMA(log(Turnover)),
    nnetar = NNETAR(log(Turnover))
  )
fit |> select(nnetar) |> gg_tsresiduals()
Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale
range (`geom_line()`).
Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale
range (`geom_point()`).
Warning: Removed 12 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
(`stat_bin()`).

The residuals from the NNETAR model have a lot of autocorrelations remaining.

fit |> select(arima) |> gg_tsresiduals()

fit |> select(ets) |> gg_tsresiduals()

The residuals from the ETS and ARIMA models have much less autocorrelation.

Let’s compare the prediction accuracy now.

fit |>
  forecast(h = "3 years", times=1) |>
  accuracy(aus_retail) |>
  select(.model, RMSE, MAE, MAPE)
Warning: The future dataset is incomplete, incomplete out-of-sample data will be treated as missing. 
24 observations are missing between 2019 Jan and 2020 Dec

The NNETAR model provides much worse forecasts than the other models.
